node.title: NT records six new COVID cases, all of them Aboriginal and one a three week old baby girl
node.alt: NT Chief Minister Michael Gunner talking at a press conference
node.description: The Northern Territory records six new COVID-19 cases, five of them in the remote community of Robinson River, Chief Minister Michael Gunner says.
node.content:
["The Northern Territory has recorded six new COVID-19 cases,\u00a0five of them in the remote community of Robinson River, Chief Minister Michael Gunner says.", "All the new cases are Aboriginal Territorians and household contacts of known cases.", "The new cases in Robinson River include a three-week-old baby girl.\u00a0The next youngest case in Robinson River is a 12-year-old girl, while the oldest is a\u00a029-year-old man.", "A 36-year-old man\u00a0from Katherine, who may have been infectious while in the community, is the sixth case.", "All new cases and their close contacts are being taken to the Howard Springs quarantine facility.", "The cluster between Katherine and Robinson River is now\u00a019 cases, according to Mr Gunner.", "\"The situation of both Robinson River and Katherine is serious,\" Mr Gunner said.", "\"We know how quickly Delta can spread within households, and we cannot be sure yet that it has not spread further into the Robinson River and Katherine communities, or wider in the Territory.\"", "New testing requirements are now in place for anyone who has\u00a0been to Robinson River since November 11.", "They must now\u00a0get tested and isolate until they receive\u00a0a negative result.", "Anyone who has left Katherine since November 7 is now also under the same requirements.", "More to come.", "", "
WA's COVID-19 reopening roadmap
